\f0\fs26 \cf0 Like the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-hybrid_system"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 two-hybrid system}}, phage display is used for the high-throughput screening of protein interactions. In the case of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M13_bacteriophage"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 M13 filamentous phage}} display, the DNA encoding the protein or peptide of interest is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_ligase"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ligated}} into the pIII or pVIII gene, encoding either the minor or major {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coat_protein"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 coat protein}}, respectively. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_cloning_site"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Multiple cloning sites}} are sometimes used to ensure that the fragments are inserted in all three possible {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reading_frames"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 reading frames}} so that the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CDNA"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cDNA}} fragment is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_translation"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 translated}} in the proper frame. The phage gene and insert {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_hybridization"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 DNA hybrid}} is then inserted (a process known as "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transformation_(genetics)"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 transformation}}") into {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escherichia_coli"}}{\fldrslt 
\i \cf2 Escherichia coli}} (E. coli) bacterial cells such as TG1, SS320, ER2738, or XL1-Blue 
\i E. coli
\i0 . If a "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phagemid"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 phagemid}}" {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_(molecular_biology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 vector}} is used (a simplified display construct vector) {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virus"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 phage particles}} will not be released from the 
\i E. coli
\i0  cells until they are infected with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helper_virus"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 helper phage}}, which enables packaging of the phage DNA and assembly of the mature {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virus"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 virions}} with the relevant protein fragment as part of their outer coat on either the minor (pIII) or major (pVIII) coat protein. By immobilizing a relevant DNA or protein target(s) to the surface of a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microtiter_plate"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 microtiter plate}} well, a phage that displays a protein that binds to one of those targets on its surface will remain while others are removed by washing. Those that remain can be {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elution"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 eluted}}, used to produce more phage (by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteria"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 bacterial}} infection with helper phage) and so produce a phage mixture that is enriched with relevant (i.e. binding) phage. The repeated cycling of these steps is referred to as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biopanning"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 'panning'}}, in reference to the enrichment of a sample of gold by removing undesirable materials. Phage eluted in the final step can be used to infect a suitable bacterial host, from which the phagemids can be collected and the relevant DNA sequence excised and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_sequencing"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sequenced}} to identify the relevant, interacting proteins or protein fragments.\
