\
Applications of phage display technology include determination of interaction partners of a protein (which would be used as the immobilised phage "bait" with a DNA library consisting of all {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coding_region"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 coding sequences}} of a cell, tissue or organism) so that the function or the mechanism of the function of that protein may be determined.
\fs22 \cf2 [7]
\fs26 \cf0  Phage display is also a widely used method for 
\i in vitro
\i0  protein evolution (also called {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein_engineering"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 protein engineering}}). As such, phage display is a useful tool in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drug_discovery"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 drug discovery}}. It is used for finding new {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ligand"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ligands}} (enzyme inhibitors, receptor agonists and antagonists) to target proteins.
\fs22 \cf2 [8][9][10]
\fs26 \cf0  The technique is also used to determine {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tumour"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 tumour}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antigens"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 antigens}} (for use in diagnosis and therapeutic targeting)
\fs22 \cf2 [11]
\fs26 \cf0  and in searching for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein-DNA_interaction"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 protein-DNA interactions}}
\fs22 \cf2 [12]
\fs26 \cf0  using specially-constructed DNA libraries with randomised segments.\
The invention of antibody phage display by laboratories at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MRC_Laboratory_of_Molecular_Biology"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology}} led by Greg Winter and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McCafferty"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 John McCafferty}} and at The Scripps Research Institute led by Richard Lerner and Carlos F. Barbas revolutionised antibody drug discovery.
\fs22 \cf2 [13][14]
\fs26 \cf0  In 1991, The Scripps group reported the first display and selection of human antibodies on phage.
\fs22 \cf2 [15]
\fs26 \cf0  This initial study described the rapid isolation of human antibody {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fragment_antigen-binding"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Fab}} that bound {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetanus_toxin"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 tetanus toxin}} and the method was then extended to rapidly clone human anti-HIV-1 antibodies for vaccine design and therapy.
\fs22 \cf2 [16][17][18][19][20]
\fs26 \cf0 \
Phage display of antibody libraries has become a powerful method for both studying the immune response as well as a method to rapidly select and evolve human antibodies for therapy. Antibody phage display was later used by Carlos F. Barbas at The Scripps Research Institute to create the first synthetic human antibody libraries, thereby allowing human antibodies to be created in vitro from synthetic diversity elements.
\fs22 \cf2 [21][22][23][24]
\fs26 \cf0 \
Antibody libraries displaying millions of different antibodies on phage are often used in the pharmaceutical industry to isolate highly specific therapeutic antibody leads, for development into antibody drugs primarily as anti-cancer or anti-inflammatory therapeutics. One of the most successful was HUMIRA ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adalimumab"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 adalimumab}}), discovered by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cambridge_Antibody_Technology"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Cambridge Antibody Technology}} as D2E7 and developed and marketed by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abbott_Laboratories"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Abbott Laboratories}}. HUMIRA, an antibody to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TNF_alpha"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 TNF alpha}}, was the world's first fully human antibody,
\fs22 \cf2 [25]
\fs26 \cf0  which achieved annual sales exceeding $1bn.
\fs22 \cf2 [26]
\fs26 \cf0 \
